```ts
function finalizeToolCall(name: string, argStr: string, hasRequiredArgs: boolean): OllamaToolCall | null {
  const s = argStr.trim();
  if (s === '') {
    // DEFECT-2 fix: '' is a legit no-arg tool ONLY when the static schema has no required props.
    // A write tool truncated AFTER the name frame but BEFORE any arg fragment yields '' too —
    // on OpenAI there is no input:{} signal to disambiguate, so REFUSE when args are required.
    return hasRequiredArgs ? null : { function: { name, arguments: {} } };
  }
  const last = s[s.length - 1];
  if (last !== '}' && last !== ']') return null;          // not terminated → REFUSE
  let parsed: unknown;
  try { parsed = JSON.parse(s); } catch { return null; }  // parse fail → REFUSE
  if (parsed === null || typeof parsed !== 'object' || Array.isArray(parsed)) return null; // DEFECT-4 fix: typeof []==='object' in JS — Array.isArray reject is REQUIRED; never {} for non-object/array
  return { function: { name, arguments: parsed as Record<string, unknown> } };
}
```
REFUSE === return null === OMIT the tool-call from StreamOnceResult.toolCalls (parser records the name into state.refusedNames). NEVER coerce to {} for a non-empty-but-unterminated/unparseable argStr — a truncated core_memory_replace/create_note/append_note at arguments:{} would fire an empty-args write under auto-apply (the L1341-1353 gate runs but on an empty object). `hasRequiredArgs` is derived from the tool's input_schema.required (toolset exposes it; verified all current write tools have required args, so a real write that truncates → either non-empty unterminated argStr → REFUSE, or name-only '' with required args → REFUSE on OpenAI). Array rejection is load-bearing AND required by the test plan (the draft's bare `typeof parsed !== 'object'` check WRONGLY passed arrays — fixed here).

CONNECTION-DROP GUARD (DEFECT-3 fix — critique 2): the frontier transport scaffold MUST NOT blindly mirror streamOnceNative's unconditional `response.on('end') → ok({...toolCalls})` (verified L1106). On a socket close AFTER content_block_start/partial input_json_delta but BEFORE content_block_stop/message_stop (or after an OpenAI name+partial-args fragment but before finish_reason), the 'end' handler runs every STILL-OPEN block buffer through finalizeToolCall (→ unterminated → REFUSE) before resolving. A missing terminal frame therefore yields ONLY finalized (terminated) tool-calls plus best-effort text — never a raw {name,argStr} buffer. Equivalently the scaffold MAY treat a terminal-frame-absent 'end' as a 'generic' ChatStreamError; either is acceptable, but the unconditional copy of L1106 is FORBIDDEN.

ABORT-PATH GUARD (FLAW-1 fix — critique 1): the frontier onAbort analog MUST resolve `toolCalls: []` (drop ALL open buffers), NOT copy streamOnceNative's L1022 `ok({ text: fullText, toolCalls, aborted:true })` which emits the raw accumulator. For native this is harmless (whole-object toolCalls; and L1254 short-circuits on res.aborted before reading res.toolCalls), but that safety is an accident of loop ordering — the frontier adapter MUST guarantee it independently. State it explicitly: abort/idle-timeout/connect-timeout settle paths resolve `{ text: fullText, toolCalls: [], aborted:true, refusal:false }`. No un-finalized buffer can ever surface even under a future loop reorder.

SYNTHETIC-NOTE / LOOP CONTRACT: a REFUSED call simply never appears in res.toolCalls, so the assistant turn pushed at L1260 carries ONLY emitted tool_calls and every emitted call gets its role:'tool' — alternation stays valid with ZERO loop edit. CRITICAL placement: the §6.6 skip happens in the PARSER (upstream of L1260), NOT the translator (FLAW-2 fix — critique 1). If an implementer put the skip in the translator, a refused call would still be in res.toolCalls, get pushed at L1260, and produce an assistant tool_use with no following tool_result → Anthropic 400 on the next turn. If a turn produced ONLY refused calls, toolCalls.length===0 → loop treats it as terminal succeed on best-effort text (acceptable), refusal STAYS false. On native this entire guard is a PERMANENT no-op (args arrive as whole objects; no argStr exists).

